The Economic and Financial Crimes Commission (EFCC), yesterday, re-arraigned one of the lawyers of former Vice-President Atiku Abubakar, Uyiekpen Giwa-Osagie, and his brother Erhunse Giwa-Osagie for allegedly laundering $2 million during the 2019 general elections. The duo, who were first arraigned before Justice Nicholas Oweibo were re-arraigned before Justice Chukwujekwu Aneke on a three-court charge of conspiracy and money laundering. They were accused by the EFCC of conspiring to make a cash payment of $2 million without going through a financial institution during the elections, saying the sum exceeded the amount authorised by law to be transacted in cash. The charges read: “That you Uyiekpen Giwa-Osagie and Erhunse Giwa-Osagie, sometimes in February 2019 in Nigeria within the jurisdiction of this honourable court, conspired to commit an offence to wit: making cash payment of the sum of $2 million without going through financial institution, which sum exceeded the amount authorised by law and you thereby committed an offence Contrary to Section 18(A), and 1(A) of the Money Laundering (Prohibition) Act, 2011 as amended and punishable under Section 16(2)(B) of the same Act. “That you Uyiekpen Giwa-Osagie, on or before the February 12, 2019, in Nigeria, within the jurisdiction of this honourable court, procured Erhunse Giwa-Osagie to make cash payment of the sum of $2 million without going through financial institution, which sum exceeded the amount authorised by law and you thereby committed an offence contrary to Section 18(C) of the Money Laundering (Prohibition) Act, 2011 as amended and punishable under Section 16(2)(B) of the same Act. “That you Erhunse Giwa-Osagie, sometimes in February 2019 in Nigeria, within the jurisdiction of this honourable court, made the payment of the sum of $2 million without going through a financial institution, which sum exceeded the amount authorised by law and you thereby committed an offence contrary to Sections 1(A). & 16(1)(D) of the Money Laundering (Prohibition) Act, 2011 (As Amended) and Punishable under Section 16 of the Same Act.”   